<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-digital-shiftreg" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Shift Registers and Counters</title>
    <p>
        Having established the behavior of flip-flops, we move on to applications that make use of these circuit elements. In particular, we will examine shift registers and the counters that are based on them.
    </p>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-digital-shiftreg-shiftreg">
        <title>Shift Registers</title>
        <p>
            Let's examine a circuit that is called a <term>shift register</term>. An example of a shift register circuit is provided in <xref ref="circuit-digital-shiftreg-shiftreg"/>
            <figure xml:id="circuit-digital-shiftreg-shiftreg">
                <caption>Shift register circuit constructed using four D flip-flops that are each triggered by the falling edge on the clock signal <m>C</m>.</caption>
                <image><latex-image>
                    <xi:include parse="text" href="./figures/circuit-digital-shiftreg-shiftreg.tex" />
                </latex-image></image>
            </figure>
            In this circuit, the input signal (In) is assumed to be controlled by some external source (another circuit or a person) and the signal can change between high and low at any time. 


            <figure xml:id="timing-digital-shiftreg-shiftreg">
                <caption></caption>
                <image width="100%">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="timing-digital-shiftreg-shiftreg-img">
                        <xi:include href="./prefigure/timing-digital-shiftreg-shiftreg.xml" />
                    </prefigure>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </p>
        
    </subsection>
    

</section>